Learning outcomes
By the end of the course, learners will be able to:

identify user, source, regulator/governance, and operator stakeholders;
define stakeholder missions, VOMR accounts, and PSKVE exchanges;
construct and interpret stakeholder MIGs;
distinguish MIG reasoning from MIG setup and coordination;
explain how Triune Intelligence drives the PUDAL Engine;
implement baseline, SOTA, and TISE simulations using reusable Python classes;
connect Ollama, OpenAI, or DeepSeek to auditable agent decisions;
design normal and disruptive experiments; and
evaluate mission achievement, value creation, equity, and resilience without overclaiming results.

2.8 Step 8 — Define objective functions
Start with separate metrics:

meal availability;
affordability;
vendor net value;
waste;
safety compliance;
average mission achievement; and
disruption retention and recovery.

Only then define an Ecosystem Value Index:
[ EVI(t)=_k w_k z_k(t). ]
Record the normalization and weights. Report component metrics beside EVI so poor performance cannot hide behind aggregation.

2.9 Step 9 — Define scenarios
At minimum include:

normal demand and supply;
demand surge;
source shortage;
operator/platform outage;
safety or regulatory restriction; and
combined disruption.

Specify onset, severity, duration, and recovery criteria before running experiments.

3.10 Step 9 — Preserve auditability
Every MIGProposal records intensity, confidence, rationale, and reasoning mode. Production extensions should additionally record:

provider and model identifier;
prompt-template version;
input-data version;
raw validated decision object;
fallback events;
policy and smart-contract version; and
random seed.

Do not store private prompts or sensitive stakeholder data without an approved data-governance design.

3.11 Step 10 — Extend to a new case
Replace, in order:

stakeholder and mission definitions;
VOMR units and update equations;
PSKVE transformation logic by subclassing PSKVEExchangeEngine;
market discovery equations;
scenario profiles;
PUDAL constraints and objective components; and
metrics and acceptance thresholds.

Keep provider adapters, coordinator interfaces, CSV output, and tests unless the new case genuinely requires a different contract.

elderly services;
education;
health care;
public transportation;
home-based business; or
another instructor-approved case.

11.6 IV. Proposed Method
Explain the method in the order a reader would implement it:

inputs and their availability at decision time;
state estimation or preprocessing;
recommendation or optimization step;
constraint checking and human authorization;
state update and recorded outputs; and
stopping or fallback behavior.

Include one architecture figure and one algorithm listing. The text should explain why each operation is necessary; the pseudocode should explain how the operations are sequenced.
Distinguish clearly among:

baseline operation;
the strongest credible fixed or state-of-the-art comparator; and
the proposed adaptive method.

Do not give the proposed method extra information, a better reasoner, or looser constraints unless that difference is itself the treatment being studied.

11.8 VI. Results
Organize results by research question rather than by file or program module. Begin each subsection with the answer, then show the evidence.
Recommended order:

verification and sanity checks;
primary comparison under normal conditions;
disruption and resilience results;
stakeholder-level distributional effects;
ablation and sensitivity analysis; and
failure cases and computational cost.

Good result sentence:

Across 30 matched seeds, TISE increased median mission achievement from 0.71 to 0.79 (absolute difference 0.08; 95% bootstrap CI [0.05, 0.11]) relative to the strongest fixed-contract comparator.

Replace the values with actual outputs. Do not use placeholders in a submitted manuscript.
Each table or figure should answer one question and remain understandable from its caption. Avoid repeating every table value in prose; state the pattern, magnitude, uncertainty, and exception.

introduce one MOEE concept;
produce one modeling artifact;
connect the artifact to one Python class;
test one claim; and
reflect on stakeholder and validity implications.
